        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title"><title type="poem" corresp="#GLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;)</title></head>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>For a presentation copy now contained in MS XI, Ruskin entitled the poem 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#GLENFARG">&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D;</title> 
                        (beginning with the line &#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;). For a copy in MS III, 
                        perhaps because he noticed that he had already used that title for another poem in the same Red Book, 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#GLENOFGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D;</title> 
                        (beginning with the line &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg thy beauteous rill&#x201D;), 
                        he titled the MS III copy of the present poem <title type="poem" corresp="#GLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D;</title>. 
                        He wrote both titles in all capital letters.</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="title_citation_note.php">System of Title Citation for Works</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>MS XI; MS III.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>January 1.</p>
                    <p><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName> questions <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s <date when="1828">1828</date> dating of the poem in <title type="book" corresp="#JRQUEENAIR">Queen of the Air</title>, reascribing it to <date when="1827-01-01">1 January 1827</date>, &#x201C;as proved by a copy in No. XI&#x201D; (PJR [<date when="1891">1891</date>], 1:?; <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRPOEMS8D1891"><title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS8D1891">PJR [8o]</title></ref>, 1:269). <persName corresp="#ETC">Cook</persName> and <persName corresp="#AW">Wedderburn</persName> accept <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>&#x02BC;s conclusions somewhat vaguely, identifying no. 22 as clearly the <date when="1828-01-01">1828</date> New Year&#x02BC;s poem, while imagining no. 23 as having &#x201C;been selected by the young author as the best specimen of his stock in hand&#x201D;&#x2014;a scenario that they then present as justification for their selecting no other work from <date when="1827">1827</date> for publication (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref> 2:260 n. 1). All of this is mistaken, however. The copy in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title> as presently bound <!--(see part 2, <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title>, &#x201C;Description&#x201D; and &#x201C;Content,&#x201D; b)--> is clearly dated <date when="1828-01-01">&#x201C;January 1 1828&#x201D;</date> in <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s hand. Collingwood may have been confused by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s entitling the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title> copy as <title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENOFGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg,&#x201D;</title> the same title as no. 2, instead of <title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D;</title> as in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>. All copies now available of no. 23 confirm a New Year&#x02BC;s presentation of <date when="1828-01-01">1828</date>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition &#x0026; Publication</head>
